Three men, including Michael Vick, pleaded innocent to dogfighting charges, while Tony Taylor changed his plea to guilty.
Taylor implicated Vick as the main financier of the operation, detailing fights sponsored or attended by Vick.
The indictment revealed gruesome details of dog killings and mistreatment.
Animal rights groups protested, and the NFL barred Vick from training camp.
Vick's sponsors suspended deals, and legal proceedings are ongoing.
The case highlights the underground world of dogfighting and its consequences for those involved, including potential prison time and financial penalties.
